Third-party content
================================================================================

This project incorporates or builds on content from several third-party sources.
Each retains its original license; the attribution requirements are summarized
below.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1. Up Goer Five vocabulary
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The ~1,000-word "Up Goer Five" vocabulary was popularized by Randall Munroe's
XKCD Simple Writer (https://xkcd.com/simplewriter/) and used in his book
"Thing Explainer" (Houghton Mifflin Harcourt, 2015). The word list itself is
not under copyright; Munroe's books and the XKCD comic are © Randall Munroe.
We use the word list only; we do not redistribute Munroe's prose.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
2. Van Cleave, "Introduction to Logic and Critical Thinking"
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Excerpts adapted into the logic-textbook benchmark in
  eval/sets/logic_textbook_bench.jsonl
are drawn from Matthew J. Van Cleave, "Introduction to Logic and Critical
Thinking v2.0" (2016). Released under Creative Commons Attribution 4.0
International (CC-BY 4.0). The source PDF is not redistributed in this
repository.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
3. Project Gutenberg sources (public domain)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The form-diversification pipeline parses public-domain translations of
philosophical texts obtained from Project Gutenberg. All are in the public
domain in the United States; many are also PD elsewhere. The parsers in
corpus/poc/parse_*.py auto-download these source files; we do not
redistribute the raw text in the repository (see .gitignore).

  - Plato, "Meno," "Crito," "Euthyphro," "Phaedo," "Gorgias,"
    "Theaetetus," "Protagoras" — Benjamin Jowett translation (1871),
    Project Gutenberg eBooks #1643, #1657, #1642, #1658, #1672, #1726, #1591.
  - Hume, David, "Dialogues Concerning Natural Religion" (1779),
    Project Gutenberg eBook #4583.
  - Aquinas, Thomas, "Summa Theologica" Part I — Fathers of the English
    Dominican Province translation (1911), Project Gutenberg eBook #17611.
  - Patrick, Mary Mills, "Sextus Empiricus and Greek Scepticism" (1899),
    Project Gutenberg eBook #17556. (Contains Patrick's English translation
    of Sextus's "Outlines of Pyrrhonism" Book I.)

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
4. cx-bot (counterexample corpus)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The counterexample passages folded into the v1 Reasoner training corpus are
drawn from the cx-bot project (https://github.com/bertybaums/good-thinking-bot)
under the same author. See its repository for that project's license.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
5. MindRouter / U-Idaho institutional infrastructure
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Teacher distillation calls were routed through the University of Idaho's
MindRouter LLM gateway, which proxies several third-party model providers
(OpenAI's gpt-oss family, Google's Gemma family, Qwen, etc.). Outputs from
those teachers are mixed into the training corpus under fair-use research
norms; no claim is made over the proprietary weights or interfaces of the
underlying providers.

